<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-420-256  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 420 256.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  April 30 1990 v9 n9 p80(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Viruses invade companies, too.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morgan, Cynthia.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software Development ShowComputer VirusesPrivately-Owned CompaniesGovernment Agency.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Viruses Invade Companies, TooandM;OAKLAND, Calif.andP;  -- Federal computer crimes probably are less numerous butmore prominent than their private-sector counterparts, despite media tales tothe contrary.andM;&quot;You always hear about a virus at NASA or a government installation, butrarely about problems at companies.andP;  That's because companies can't afford totalk about it.andP;  There are too many people at government sites with too littleinterest in shutting it up,&quot; said Robert Clyde, a computer crime investigatorand consultant.andM;In a seminar at the Software Development '90 conference last month, Clydesaid federal computers, particularly in secured areas, are more likely to bevirus-free than their commercial counterparts.andP;  Once problems occur, mostgovernment agencies have emergency programs ready to deal with them, he said,unlike many commercial installations.andM;In fact, Clyde said, much of the computer virus problem may be a mediaexaggeration.andM;&quot;Computer viruses are becoming the lazy student's excuse for not turning inhis homework, but they are just not that common yet.andP;  The Columbus Day viruswas all over the news, but I know of only two systems that were hit,&quot; hesaid.andM;Frustrated users may blame computer malfunctions on a virus when the realproblems is buggy software or hardware breakdowns, Clyde said.andM;The steps needed to clean up traces of computer vandalism often are identicalto standard repair practices.andP;  Such techniques also remove any trace of theproblem, making substantiation of such cases difficult, he said.andM;&quot;So far, I've seen relatively little serious damage,&quot; Clyde said.andP;  &quot;However,it's just a matter of time.andP;  In reality, at most sites security is stillreally terrible.andP;  It's only because there are relatively few real virusproblems so far that we've avoided a major catastrophe.&quot;andM;Clyde said the best way to prevent future disasters is to augment datamanagers' authority along the lines of the federal Orange Book standards fora C2 security rating.andP;  System access privileges should be restricted to thosewho need to make operational changes regularly.andM;&quot;A lot of times we grant privilege to make people feel more important.andP;  Weought to call it 'liability' instead of 'privilege', because that's what itis,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;I went to a site with nearly 7,000 users on VAX clusters.andP;  Two hundred ofthem were privileged.andP;  Less than 20 really needed to be.andP;  How can anyonemaintain a scure system that way?&quot; he asked.andO;</TEXT></DOC>